Of course. I'd be happy to guide you through deploying your website on GitHub. It's a great way to host your portfolio for free.

While I can't perform these actions on your behalf for security reasons (I don't have access to your personal accounts), I can give you a clear, step-by-step guide to get your site live. It's easier than it sounds!

Heres how you can deploy your portfolio using the GitHub web interface, no command-line needed:

Step-by-Step Guide to Deploying on GitHub Pages

Step 1: Create a GitHub Repository

A repository (or "repo") is like a folder for your project.

  1. Go to GitHub.com and log in. If you don't have an account, you'll need to create one.

  2. On the main page, click the + icon in the top-right corner and select "New repository".

  3. This is the most important step: For the "Repository name", you must name it exactly like this:
    your-github-username.github.io
    (For example, if your username is mnourelisy, the repository name must be mnourelisy.github.io).

  4. Make sure the repository is set to Public.

  5. You can skip all other options (like adding a README).

  6. Click "Create repository".

Step 2: Upload Your Website Files

Now you'll upload the files I've provided into your new repository.

  1. In your new repository, click on the "Add file" button and choose "Upload files".

  2. Drag and drop all four of your website files (index.html, index.css, index.tsx, and metadata.json) into the browser window.

  3. Once the files are uploaded, scroll to the bottom and click "Commit changes".

Step 3: Enable GitHub Pages

This tells GitHub to treat this repository as a live website.

  1. In your repository, click on the "Settings" tab (it's in the top navigation bar of the repo).

  2. In the left-hand menu, click on "Pages".

  3. Under "Build and deployment", for the "Source", make sure it says "Deploy from a branch".

  4. Under "Branch", select main (it might be master on older accounts) and leave the folder as / (root). Click "Save".

Step 4: Your Website is Live!

That's it! Your website is now being published. It might take a minute or two to go live.

You can access it at the URL:
https://your-github-username.github.io

You can refresh the "Settings" > "Pages" screen, and it will show you the exact URL once it's ready.

Step 5: Update the Sharing URL in Your Code

Now that you have your live URL, you need to update the social sharing links in your index.html file so they work correctly.

  1. Go back to the main page of your repository (the "Code" tab).

  2. Click on the index.html file.

  3. Click the pencil icon (Edit this file) in the top-right corner of the file view.

  4. Scroll down to the <footer> section near the bottom.

  5. Find the lines with YOUR_WEBSITE_URL_HERE and replace that placeholder with your actual live URL (e.g., https://mnourelisy.github.io).

  6. Scroll to the top or bottom of the page and click "Commit changes".

Now, when anyone clicks the share buttons on your portfolio, it will link to your live website. Congratulations, you've successfully deployed your professional portfolio
